Description columns name and content¶

1-popularity :The MOVIEmeter rank of a film is a measure of popularity. It is essentially based on page views of pages related to a film. ex 2,376,452 IMDb users have given a weighted average vote of 9.3 / 10
2- run time : Runtime is the time between the starting of the movie upto the end of the credits scene. It does not include any trailers and break
3- tagline : is a short, memorable phrase used in marketing campaigns to convey the value of a brand or its products.
4- vote_count: number of people who vote in imdb

From first look at data¶

1- there are nan and 0 value in columns
2- the columns like run_time and revenue and budget don`t contain any unit so I will take Doller and minute to unite
3- there are un necessary columns for our analysis imdb_id,homepage, keywords, overview,run time and more we need to delete them
4- there are columns contain several values, which are seperated by "|" like cast ,director,genres,production_companie we need to clean it

Data Cleaning¶

After discussing the structure of the data and any problems that need to be cleaned, perform those cleaning steps in the second part of this section.

Deal with 0 and nan value¶

from discribe() we can see that from min ,25% ,50% in column budget revenue runtime budget_adj revenue_adj contain "0"
so we will replace "0 " with NaN and then drop this column

In [70]:
#list of this columns
drop_list = ['budget','revenue','runtime','budget_adj','revenue_adj']
#replace "0" with nan
df[drop_list] = df[drop_list].replace(0,np.NAN)
#drop nan 
df.dropna(subset= drop_list  ,inplace = True)

#create  unique genres 
date_set=set()
genres_set=set()
year_release = df_genres_dates['release_year'].drop_duplicates()
#to create unique year and put it into set
for y in year_release :
   date_set.add(y)
date_set
#to create unique genres and put it into set
for y in year_release :
    genres_dict ={}
    genres_year=df_genres_dates[df_genres_dates['release_year']== y]
    genres_year =  genres_year["genres"].values
    for item in genres_year :
        genres_place =item.split('|')
        for ge in genres_place:
            if ge not in genres_set:
                genres_set.add(ge)
                
df_countgenres_year =pd.DataFrame(index=date_set ,columns =genres_set)
#because we didn`t put  value in data  so it will be nan
# to replace nan with 0
df_countgenres_year[:] = 0
##create a dataframe  contains the sum of  genre for every year
for y in year_release :
    genres_dict ={}
    genres_year=df_genres_dates[df_genres_dates['release_year']== y]
    genres_year =  genres_year["genres"].values
    for item in genres_year :
        genres_place =item.split('|')
        for ge in genres_place:
            if ge not in genres_dict :
                genres_dict[ge]=1
            else :
    #add sum of generes to dict            
                genres_dict[ge]= genres_dict[ge]+1
                
#creat dataframe from genres_dict
 

    df_dict_genres=pd.DataFrame(genres_dict ,index =[y])            

    df_countgenres_year.loc[y,df_dict_genres.columns] = df_countgenres_year.loc[y,df_dict_genres.columns] + df_dict_genres.loc[y]

df_countgenres_year

#function to calculat and draw coefficient-of-correlation
def pl_coor_map(df_revenue ):
    corr_map = df_revenue.corr()
    _ , axis = plt.subplots( figsize =( 18 , 10 ) )
    pl_map = sns.color_palette("ch:start=.2,rot=-.3", as_cmap=True)
    _ = sns.heatmap(corr_map,cmap = pl_map,square=True, cbar_kws={ 'shrink' : .9 }, ax=axis, annot = True, annot_kws = { 'fontsize' : 14 })

where Budget vs Revenue¶

Revenue increases slightly at higher levels but the number of high-budget films appears to be rare. There is a good chance that movies with higher investment will lead to better returns.

where the Correlation is 0.55

vote average vs revenu¶

The relationship between them is very weak, and the revenu do not seem to change with a higher average revenu The correlation between them and vote average is 0.297.

Popularity vs Revenue¶

Revenue appears to increase with popularity. you can say that when a movie's popularity high, then the movie's revenue might be high

where the Correlation is 0.51

Runtime vs Revenue¶

The relationship between them is very weak, and the revenu do not seem to change with a higher average revenu The correlation between them and runtime is 0.2465

Conclusions¶

1- Drama is the most popular genre, following by Mystery, comedy and action¶
2- most frequent year 2011 that mean The year I achieved most films profits 2011¶
3-Average the best ratio for the runtime is 116.189 m = 116.189/60 = 2 h¶
4-The most profitable film director is Steven Spielberg¶
5-The most profitable genres is Comedy¶
6- the best movies in imbd based on the revenu that make is avatar than star wars and titanic¶
7-the best movies in imbd based on their popularity is jurassic world than mad max fury road and interstellar¶
8-avrage of revenues for the movies 107,686,616.09807¶
9- Revenue is directly linked to the budget¶
10-Average movie RUN time is decreasing year by year.¶
11-The production companies Warner Bros, Universal Pictures, and Paramount Pictures are making more money than the other production companies.¶

LIMITION¶

This dataset is very informative. This analysis was done with the understanding that this may not be completely error-free. Some of the limitations that the dataset has are null and zero values in some features. They should be removed from the rows Moreover, we are not sure if the data provided to us is completely correct and up-to-date. And also The Budget and Revenue column does not contain a currency unit, it may be possible for different movies to have a budget in different currency according to the country so there is a difference that could indicate an error in the complete analysis. But his year is clear to us from Data set . That we have a high probability of achieving high profits if we have characteristics similar to what was found in the analysis. If we release a movie with these characteristics
